<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-545-971  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 545 971.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Business Week  Nov 5 1990 n3186 p140(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PC makers have a virus: the threats of recession and war areslowing growth to a standstill. (includes related article oneffects on computer resellers) (Information Processing -Computers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Depke, Deidre A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Sales of microcomputers are slowing as the US economy enters whatmany call a recession and the possibility of war in the MiddleEast grows.andP;  Computer manufacturers are familiar with growth ratesof 20-30 percent.andP;  In the 1990s, predictions of annual growth ofeven 10 percent in the industry may be overly optimistic.andO;Microcomputer sales to US businesses are estimated to be generallyflat, with declines in some areas and very minor increases inothers.andP;  Network file servers and laptop computers are sellingreasonably well but regular desktop microcomputers, the baseproduct for the industry, are doing very poorly.andP;  Even IBM shows asmall drop in 3rd qtr 1990 revenues, which it and analystsattribute to the decline in microcomputer sales.andP;  Demand inEurope, while still increasing at an annual rate of 18 percent, ishalf what it was in 1989.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer industryMicrocomputersComputer ManufactureSalesRecessionIndustry Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Domestic PC sales flatten out. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>